fcg
Concord, MA9 contributions
The Mouffetard I love
May 2022
Responding in part to scotlandmac's negative post. I live part-time in this neighborhood, and I'd like everyone to love it as I do. Different neighborhoods in Paris have different characteristics, and neighborhoods are different on different days of the week. The Mouffetard area is a mix of middle-to-upper income families, all ages, and students (nearby Sorbonne, Science colleges, etc.). It is a true neighborhood, not a high-end shopping or touristic neighborhood. If you walk the length of the pedestrian street (a few blocks), you really get a feel for all dimensions of the neighborhood. Place Contrescarpe at the north end is the perfect coffee-and-people-watching square, with a half-dozen cafs. Along the northern half of the street, there are more take-out places (Greek, crepes, sandwiches), because this is closer to the universities. Along the southern half of the street, there are more restaurants and great shops, including high end chocolates and wines, clothing and teas. At the southernmost end, there's another beautiful flowery square with a perfect kids' playground, cafs - and on Sundays about 11:30, live accordion music and dancing! Sunday afternoons and Monday, many shops are closed, as in many neighborhoods. Sunday morning is the most lively, but all the other days of the week are great too. And about markets - rue Mouffetard is more a "market street" than an open-air street market. The fresh-produce vendors are mostly in storefronts all along the street, rather than stalls in a temporary market. For the local temporary market, go to the Monge Market two blocks off Mouffetard, WedFriSun approx 7-1. Enjoy!
Written May 19, 2022
